we accomplish great tasks,

00:51:22.000 --> 00:51:25.000
do great things
like, uh, poetry,

00:51:25.000 --> 00:51:29.000
like novels,
like music, et cetera.

00:51:29.000 --> 00:51:33.000
( playing Mozart sonata )

00:51:35.000 --> 00:51:38.000
SEVERSON:
Dr. Noble wants us to think
of our genetic inheritance

00:51:38.000 --> 00:51:42.000
as just a part
of what makes us what we are.

00:51:42.000 --> 00:51:45.000
( sonata continuing )

00:51:45.000 --> 00:51:47.000
NOBLE:
When somebody sits down
and plays at the piano,

00:51:47.000 --> 00:51:51.000
the strings of the piano
are like your DNA.

00:51:51.000 --> 00:51:53.000
You can make the tone louder,

00:51:53.000 --> 00:51:57.000
you can make it softer,
smoother, et cetera.

00:52:01.000 --> 00:52:04.000
And you need the two to give you
the balance of life.

00:52:04.000 --> 00:52:07.000
And that's what results
in your personality.

00:52:07.000 --> 00:52:11.000
SEVERSON:
In his metaphor, the strings
of the piano are our genes.

00:52:11.000 --> 00:52:12.000
The impact of our environment

00:52:12.000 --> 00:52:16.000
is represented by the pedals
controlling how the notes sound,

00:52:16.000 --> 00:52:19.000
but the third factor is
the pianist's personal style.

00:52:19.000 --> 00:52:21.000
NOBLE:
The emotion that person puts in,

00:52:21.000 --> 00:52:24.000
that finally results
in you sitting as an audience

00:52:24.000 --> 00:52:26.000
and listening to this person,

00:52:26.000 --> 00:52:28.000
see how beautifully
