00:52:28.000 --> 00:52:31.000
SEVERSON:
It's this concert
of genes and environment

00:52:31.000 --> 00:52:34.000
that separates those
who are elated by Mozart

00:52:34.000 --> 00:52:37.000
and those who go to greater
lengths, or heights,

00:52:37.000 --> 00:52:38.000
to collect their thrills.

00:52:45.000 --> 00:52:47.000
OBERLE:
The sky diver in me

00:52:47.000 --> 00:52:50.000
does not want to consider
skydiving as risk taking.

00:52:50.000 --> 00:52:53.000
But I think that in taking risks
you feel more alive.

00:52:53.000 --> 00:52:56.000
That if just going
through life conservatively,

00:52:56.000 --> 00:52:59.000
and, you know,
you don't experience

00:52:59.000 --> 00:53:02.000
a wide range of emotions,
that there's, uh...

00:53:02.000 --> 00:53:04.000
you know,
it's stagnant, it's static.

00:53:04.000 --> 00:53:09.000
Whereas opposed to risk-taking
in a general sense

00:53:09.000 --> 00:53:13.000
you know, it creates a more
fulfilling, dynamic experience.

00:53:16.000 --> 00:53:18.000
It's obvious that
some people

00:53:18.000 --> 00:53:21.000
are just naturally better
at sports than others.

00:53:21.000 --> 00:53:24.000
They can run faster or farther
or develop bigger muscles.

00:53:24.000 --> 00:53:26.000
Why?

00:53:26.000 --> 00:53:30.000
Well, that and a lot else is
determined by our metabolism--

00:53:30.000 --> 00:53:32.000
things like breathing,
heart rate, blood flow.

00:53:32.000 --> 00:53:35.000
And our metabolism
is determined by our genes,

00:53:35.000 --> 00:53:39.000
including two variants of
a very important gene named ACE.

00:53:39.000 --> 00:53:42.000
I'm sure the computer
would love to tell us about it.

00:53:42.000 --> 00:53:47.000
COMPUTER:
Well, Lucky, ACE stands for
angiotensin-converting enzyme,

00:53:47.000 --> 00:53:49.000
a key element
of the circulation system

00:53:49.000 --> 00:53:51.000
that dictates blood pressure.

00:53:51.000 --> 00:53:56.000
Human beings have two ACE genes,
one inherited from each parent.

00:53:56.000 --> 00:53:59.000
Each of these has variants
labeled I or D.

00:53:59.000 --> 00:54:03.000
There are three
possible combinations.

00:54:03.000 --> 00:54:07.000
The I variant makes less ACE,
the D variant makes more.

00:54:07.000 --> 00:54:11.000
DDs tend to have higher
blood pressure, IIs lower.

00:54:11.000 --> 00:54:16.000
For most people, high
blood pressure is undesirable.

00:54:16.000 --> 00:54:20.000
It is associated with
heart disease and stroke.

00:54:20.000 --> 00:54:22.000
So, is there
an evolutionary reason

00:54:22.000 --> 00:54:25.000
that some produce higher levels
of ACE than others?

00:54:25.000 --> 00:54:26.000
COMPUTER:
Good question.

00:54:26.000 --> 00:54:29.000
There may have been
an adaptive advantage

00:54:29.000 --> 00:54:31.000
to having high levels of ACE.

00:54:31.000 --> 00:54:33.000
If you were unfortunate enough

00:54:33.000 --> 00:54:36.000
to have had a leg bitten off
by a saber-toothed tiger

00:54:36.000 --> 00:54:38.000
or experienced hemorrhage
in childbirth,

00:54:39.000 --> 00:54:42.000
the increased blood pressure
of high-ACE-level individuals

00:54:42.000 --> 00:54:44.000
would help them survive.

00:54:50.000 --> 00:54:53.000
SEVERSON:
The relationship
between ACE and blood pressure

00:54:53.000 --> 00:54:54.000
has been known for some time.

00:54:55.000 --> 00:54:57.000
A family of drugs
called ACE inhibitors

00:54:57.000 --> 00:55:00.000
have proved successful in
controlling high blood pressure

00:55:00.000 --> 00:55:03.000
by lowering the levels
of ACE in the body.

00:55:03.000 --> 00:55:06.000
To a doctor
at London's University College,

00:55:06.000 --> 00:55:10.000
those results suggest that
something else is going on, too.

00:55:10.000 --> 00:55:14.000
MAN:
The death rates were at least
halved by the ACE inhibitors,

00:55:14.000 --> 00:55:17.000
so they were doing
something else magical,

00:55:17.000 --> 00:55:19.000
and no one at that stage
knew what that was.

00:55:19.000 --> 00:55:22.000
SEVERSON:
Hugh Montgomery's lab is devoted

00:55:22.000 --> 00:55:25.000
to exploring the genes that
affect the heart and its growth.

00:55:25.000 --> 00:55:28.000
MONTGOMERY:
Heart growth itself
in disease states

00:55:28.000 --> 00:55:30.000
is almost universally
a bad thing.

00:55:30.000 --> 00:55:34.000
And the bigger the heart gets,
the more likely you are to die.

00:55:34.000 --> 00:55:36.000
Part of that is explicable
by the fact

00:55:36.000 --> 00:55:39.000
that you've just got
an awful lot more heart muscle

00:55:39.000 --> 00:55:41.000
and it gets a lot of
collagen, or scarring,

00:55:41.000 --> 00:55:43.000
between the muscle cells

00:55:43.000 --> 00:55:45.000
and it seems just to function
less well over time.

00:55:45.000 --> 00:55:53.000
What we can see here is
a cardiac MRI of a normal heart.

00:55:53.000 --> 00:55:56.000
SEVERSON:
The right ventricle pumps
blood to the lungs,

00:55:56.000 --> 00:56:00.000
but the left ventricle,
shown here as this dark ring,

00:56:00.000 --> 00:56:01.000
has to do all the work

00:56:01.000 --> 00:56:04.000
of supplying blood
to the rest of the body.

00:56:04.000 --> 00:56:07.000
The left ventricle here
is of normal thickness.

00:56:07.000 --> 00:56:09.000
The MRI of
a thickened heart shows

00:56:09.000 --> 00:56:11.000
just how much more
work it has to do

00:56:11.000 --> 00:56:13.000
to keep the circulation going.

00:56:13.000 --> 00:56:18.000
You can see, although the heart
looks relatively smaller here,

00:56:18.000 --> 00:56:21.000
this wall of the left ventricle

00:56:21.000 --> 00:56:23.000
is definitely thicker
and is making the cavity,

00:56:23.000 --> 00:56:26.000
which is full of fluid,
actually look smaller.

00:56:26.000 --> 00:56:29.000
if you have a thicker heart
muscle, more heart growth,

00:56:29.000 --> 00:56:32.000
you are much more likely to have
a heart attack,

00:56:32.000 --> 00:56:33.000
or to get peripheral
vascular disease,

00:56:33.000 --> 00:56:36.000
or kidney failure or
to have a stroke.

00:56:36.000 --> 00:56:39.000
And we don't know what's
connecting those two things.

00:56:39.000 --> 00:56:42.000
If we can find out what
makes hearts grow,

00:56:42.000 --> 00:56:44.000
then we can find out
perhaps what's also

00:56:44.000 --> 00:56:46.000
causing strokes and
heart attacks.

00:56:47.000 --> 00:56:48.000
Animal studies suggested
that the ace gene

00:56:49.000 --> 00:56:51.000
had something to do with
heart growth.

00:56:51.000 --> 00:56:53.000
But when it came time to do
human studies,

00:56:53.000 --> 00:56:55.000
the options
were limited.

00:56:55.000 --> 00:57:00.000
The only way in which one could
do that was to use the ace gene

00:57:00.000 --> 00:57:03.000
as a measure of differences of
ace activity in heart muscle

00:57:03.000 --> 00:57:06.000
because you can't otherwise
measure in a human.

00:57:06.000 --> 00:57:09.000
You can't go around taking
pieces of heart muscle out.

00:57:09.000 --> 00:57:11.000
But there was another way to
approach it.

00:57:11.000 --> 00:57:15.000
The heart is a muscle and
muscles grow with exercise.

00:57:15.000 --> 00:57:18.000
What if we could measure
the effects of exercise on

00:57:18.000 --> 00:57:20.000
heart size and
match that against

00:57:20.000 --> 00:57:22.000
their ace gene
expression.

00:57:22.000 --> 00:57:28.000
Then we'd know whether ace
affects heart growth.

00:57:28.000 --> 00:57:31.000
Enter the British Army.

00:57:31.000 --> 00:57:35.000
New army recruits were
the perfect control

00:57:35.000 --> 00:57:37.000
sample for this
experiment.

00:57:37.000 --> 00:57:39.000
They're all roughly
the same age

00:57:39.000 --> 00:57:41.000
and during their
basic training they live a

00:57:41.000 --> 00:57:47.000
highly regulated,
identical lifestyle.

00:57:47.000 --> 00:57:50.000
Over twelve weeks the recruits
were put through paces

00:57:50.000 --> 00:58:02.000
with a combination of strength
and endurance training.

00:58:02.000 --> 00:58:05.000
Samples of DNA were
taken from the recruits

00:58:05.000 --> 00:58:07.000
and sent to the
lab at London.

00:58:07.000 --> 00:58:09.000
In the meantime the
young soldiers

00:58:09.000 --> 00:58:11.000
continued their
training.

00:58:11.000 --> 00:58:15.000
Their heart and skeletal muscle
mass was measured periodically.

00:58:15.000 --> 00:58:17.000
At first the results simply
seamed to confirm

00:58:17.000 --> 00:58:21.000
what the researchers were
expecting to find.

00:58:21.000 --> 00:58:22.000
Well the first thing
that we identified

00:58:22.000 --> 00:58:27.000
was that we found that the two
D versions of the ace gene,

00:58:27.000 --> 00:58:29.000
high ace activity was
associated with much greater

00:58:29.000 --> 00:58:31.000
heart growth with
exercise.

00:58:31.000 --> 00:58:34.000
The two I versions of the ace
gene, low ace activity

00:58:34.000 --> 00:58:37.000
associated with much
less heart growth.

00:58:37.000 --> 00:58:39.000
So the study demonstrated
that levels of ace

00:58:39.000 --> 00:58:42.000
did indeed control
heart growth.

00:58:42.000 --> 00:58:45.000
The recruits with higher levels
of ace built up bigger muscles

00:58:45.000 --> 00:58:47.000
including their
heart muscles.

00:58:47.000 --> 00:58:50.000
But the surprising finding was
that those with low ace levels

00:58:50.000 --> 00:58:54.000
developed much
better stamina.

00:58:54.000 --> 00:58:58.000
At the end of training we found
very dramatic effects.

00:58:58.000 --> 00:59:00.000
The iis, the low ace
activity people

00:59:00.000 --> 00:59:03.000
had doubled their
duration exercise.

00:59:03.000 --> 00:59:04.000
And the poor old
DDs actually were

00:59:04.000 --> 00:59:06.000
no better off at the
end of ten weeks

00:59:06.000 --> 00:59:10.000
of military training then they
were at the start.

00:59:10.000 --> 00:59:14.000
So low ace activity made your
muscles more fatigue resistant.

00:59:14.000 --> 00:59:16.000
And these were big
findings if you view

00:59:16.000 --> 00:59:18.000
the heart as the ultimate
endurance muscle.

00:59:18.000 --> 00:59:21.000
It's got to beat maybe
100 times a minute

00:59:21.000 --> 00:59:25.000
for lets say
hopefully 105 years.

00:59:25.000 --> 00:59:27.000
Not altogether
surprising therefore

00:59:27.000 --> 00:59:29.000
that perhaps low ace
activity is beneficial

00:59:29.000 --> 00:59:31.000
to heart as an
endurance muscle.

00:59:31.000 --> 00:59:33.000
And we began to wonder
whether in fact

00:59:33.000 --> 00:59:35.000
if that's what ace
inhibitors were doing.

00:59:35.000 --> 00:59:38.000
They were helping this endurance
characteristic of the muscle.

00:59:38.000 --> 00:59:40.000
Part of the recruits
training program involves

00:59:40.000 --> 00:59:43.000
running 1 1/2 miles
at maximum speed

00:59:43.000 --> 00:59:47.000
at the start of the twelve weeks
training and again at the end.

00:59:47.000 --> 00:59:50.000
Once again the recruits with
low ace activity developed

00:59:50.000 --> 00:59:52.000
greater endurance and
dramatically improved

00:59:52.000 --> 00:59:54.000
their run times.

00:59:54.000 --> 00:59:56.000
That means the ace
gene is affecting

00:59:56.000 --> 00:59:59.000
the entire
metabolic system.

00:59:59.000 --> 01:00:00.000
We can now see there
are large advantages

01:00:00.000 --> 01:00:03.000
to low levels of ace activity.

01:00:03.000 --> 01:00:06.000
The ace gene variation will
partly explain peoples

01:00:06.000 --> 01:00:09.000
response to exercise but
it's not "the gene"

01:00:09.000 --> 01:00:13.000
for exercise performance.

01:00:13.000 --> 01:00:15.000
I think we are a long way off
that sort of genetic selection

01:00:15.000 --> 01:00:18.000
of exercise training.

01:00:18.000 --> 01:00:21.000
Much better in fact to say that
exercise is good for everybody

01:00:21.000 --> 01:00:24.000
and aerobic training is
the best sort of exercise

01:00:24.000 --> 01:00:27.000
and that we should
all do it.

01:00:28.000 --> 01:00:30.000
So don''t give up the gym
membership just yet.

01:00:30.000 --> 01:00:32.000
In the meantime we 'll
keep you updated on further

01:00:32.000 --> 01:00:36.000
research developments with
this two faced gene.

01:00:36.000 --> 01:00:39.000
Genetics, confusing,
controversial

01:00:39.000 --> 01:00:41.000
and always complicated.

